statements: SELECT * FROM summary_statistics;
SELECT id, dataset_name, numerical_attribute1 FROM summary_statistics;
SELECT dataset_name, numerical_attribute2, id FROM summary_statistics ORDER BY numerical_attribute2 DESC;
SELECT id, dataset_name, numerical_attribute1, numerical_attribute2 FROM summary_statistics WHERE dataset_name = 'example';
SELECT id, dataset_name, numerical_attribute1, numerical_attribute2 FROM summary_statistics WHERE numerical_attribute1 < 50 ORDER BY numerical_attribute1 DESC;
SELECT * FROM summary_statistics WHERE numerical_attribute1 > 100 ORDER BY dataset_name DESC;
SELECT dataset_name, AVG(numerical_attribute1) AS avg_num_attr1 FROM summary_statistics GROUP BY dataset_name HAVING COUNT(*) > 10;
SELECT dataset_name, numerical_attribute1, numerical_attribute2 FROM summary_statistics WHERE dataset_name LIKE 'A%' AND numerical_attribute1 < 50 ORDER BY numerical_attribute2 ASC;
SELECT dataset_name, numerical_attribute1 FROM summary_statistics WHERE numerical_attribute2 IS NOT NULL AND numerical_attribute1 BETWEEN 50 AND 100 ORDER BY dataset_name ASC;
SELECT COUNT(*) AS total_rows, MAX(numerical_attribute1) AS max_num_attr1, MIN(numerical_attribute1) AS min_num_attr1 FROM summary_statistics;

SELECT ds.id, st.mean, st.median, sa.analysis_status FROM dataset ds JOIN statistics st ON ds.id = st.dataset_id JOIN data_analysis sa ON sa.dataset_id = ds.id WHERE st.mean > 50 AND sa.analysis_status = 'completed' ORDER BY st.mean DESC;

SELECT ds.id, SUM(sr.summary_value) AS total_summary_value FROM dataset ds JOIN statistics st ON st.dataset_id = ds.id JOIN summary_results sr ON sr.statistics_id = st.id GROUP BY ds.id HAVING total_summary_value > 500 ORDER BY total_summary_value ASC;
